sentences: Aref Arefkia (Persian: عارف عارف‌کیا) (Azerbaijani: Arif Arifkiya), known as Aref (Persian: عارف; also Romanized as Āref, born August 10, 1940) is an Iranian pop music singer and former actor.
He graduated from Tehran Industrial School of Art in 1958.
In the 1960s, Aref introduced a new wave of romantic styles to the large spectrum of romantic Persian music.
Aref and his family left Iran in 1979, following the Islamic revolution.

Triphony song "Hamoumi": The folk song was set in 1974 by Shamaezadeh, played by Aref, Ebi and Solly.

Six-voiced song "Iran" (Vatan janeh man_jaanam Irane man): The song was produced and released in 1988 with a poem by Homayoun Hoshyarnejad and a song by Shamaei-zadeh in a shortcoming called "Peace(=Solh)" by Pars Video, whose singers were Aref, Vigen, Shamaei-zadeh, Hooshmand Aghili and Shifteh.
Song "Music": The song was recorded in collaboration with 24 Iranian artists produced by Tapesh-TV in 2006.
The song was released in 1967 and topped the best-selling songs for weeks.
"Lake of Light (=Daryache-Noor)": The song was performed and released in 1968 with a beautiful melody by Parviz Maqsadi.
"Daryache-Noor" was ranked second in the best song of 1968 by the singers of "Majale-Javanan" ( famous Iranian journal ), which made Aref more popular.

New Persian Songs : In the early 1970s, great songwriters such as Shahyar Ghanbari, Ardalan Sarfaraz and Iraj Jannati-Ataei began to change the course of songs and used heavy Persian literature.
In the 1960s and 1970s, most of the selway choruses of Aref songs were performed by a woman named Hermineh.
Before starting his career as a singer, Aref worked as a teacher in Qazvin industrial school of art for two years, but the truth is that he has been singing since he was 12 years old.
He first lived in London, England, for three years, then moved to Los Angeles, United States.
Song Style :In the past,  Aref's work was known among music pursuers as "Aref style.".
In the early 1950s, love songs were performed with Western orchestration and Persian theology.

In a survey conducted by Javanan Magazine, Aref and Googoosh were both chosen as "Most Famous Pop Icon" of the year, nine years in a row.
Zan-e Rooz magazine chose Aref as Man of the Year from a large group of politicians, singers and actors.
His songs were heard on numerous Iranian films of the 1960s and early 1970s among which Gholam Jandarm, Soltan-e Ghalbha, Ghesseh-e Shab, Yaghout-e 3 Chashm, Dalahoo and Gharibeh are the most famous.
